DURBAN - THE KwaZulu-Natal Department of Transport has urged parents to be vigilant about the safety of the vehicles used to transport pupils.Kwanele Ncalane, spokesperson for the department, said: “We appeal to parents to play their role because they are the ones who commission these drivers in their localities or areas of residence, therefore they know these vehicles and these drivers. So we are calling on them as well to assist us by making sure that learners are transported in reliable, roadworthy, legal and safe vehicles,” said Ncalane.Ncalane was speaking after an accident claimed two children’s lives when a taxi carrying pupils and a truck collided on the R103, near Rosetta, on Friday afternoon.Midlands EMS said on Friday that reports from the scene indicated that the taxi was transporting children home from school when the crash occurred. Two children were declared dead at the scene. Six were injured.Ncalane said the department had adopted a programme to ensure the safety of school transport. “In the mornings and in the afternoons, we have operations that are running in the province and our focus is on the issue of overloading. We have engaged with the taxi industry on this matter, but we will be strengthening enforcement,” said Ncalane.MORE ON THISPICS: Two learners killed, six injured in PMB crashHe said the department was dealing with the issue of individuals assuming the responsibility of transporting pupils as school transport drivers needed to be vetted by the department.Deputy mayor for uMngeni Municipality, Sandile Mnikathi, urged drivers to be cautious. Provincial police spokesperson Lieutenant-Colonel Nqobile Gwala confirmed the incident.“Charges of culpable homicide and drunken driving are being investigated by Nottingham Road SAPS. It is alleged that a taxi that was transporting schoolchildren collided with a truck on the R103 Old Main Road. Two children aged 10 and 14 were declared dead at the scene,” said Gwala. She added that a 21-year-old suspect, who was driving the taxi, would appear in the Howick Magistrate’s Court today.THE MERCURY